This is just an extruder mount to make the mk8 compatible with j-head groove mount also compatible with the link to the original design. The original design were off to the right by the designer because he wanted to have the motor rest on the hot end mount but I don't prefer that because I would lose some print volumes by about 5-10mm (which isn't that great to be honest). So I just trace along all the lines and recreated another that sits at the center (slightly to the left of original mk8 mount position by about 3-5mm) so that I don't have to mess with the printable area for x axis. For this, you just have to take out the existing fan and heatsink and reuse the longer screw again As of now, this design would remain as experimental until I get my e3d although I already have all metal j-head, but keep changing hot ends would require a lot of calibration and rewiring to be done. But this item should work fine. I only redesigned the groove mount for mk8 extruder compatible. description.text: After having arms slowly deflect up on me I began to look for a more permanent solution. There are several different types of aluminum and ABS models out there. I took my MK8 design, added the pin and tab found on Whpthomas's version, and made a few modifications to get it printable at Shapeways in stainless steel. I know there were possible tolerance issues considering Shapeways gives a very large tolerance. The part I received measured very close (within .15mm), If you have this made, bear in mind the possible tolerance issue.

I had front arm printed at Shapeway's http://www.shapeways.com/model/1049270/mk8-extruder-arm.html?li=productBox-search I printed off the back piece in PLA. I never see any warping on the back piece. It is basically a spacer and holds the spring. I also did not want to add the extra weight. Materials:
3x10x4 Bearing
10mm M3 button head bolt
M3 nut
small washer
flat head m3 x10 bolt
compression spring. I am using this one a jones spring:
http://www.springsfast.com/part_detail_compression.php?part=C12-041-040&PHPSESSID=542e09c99ec81bbb617ba42c4462f283 I bought the spring from mcmaster carr as part # 9657K333 This works just like all the other extruder modifications. I printed the pin upside down. It only lays a single circle on the first layer, but it printed fine because it is so small so it didn't fall over. Use the flat head on the top right of the stepper to hold the back piece on. The hole for the bearing screw I made purposely a little small so I could try to tap threads in it. It took threads but it is not something I would not trust it so I also put the nut on the back. Use one of the original bolts to hold on the arm with the pin placed inside. I put a little grease on the pin as well. Insert spring and bolt it all back together. It took up all the space available and I was going to print a slightly narrower back in order to give a little more space, but it has been printing for about 40 hours now without issue so I have not done that .

description.text: This mount is a platform for attaching electronic devices to motorcycle handlebars.  This was designed for a Yamaha XJ650, but may work for other bikes.  The D123 CAD files are included so modifications can be made.

Others materials used:
6-32 threaded rod (2 each)
6-32 nuts (4 each) This is printed in PLA, 6 vertical shells, 6 horizontal shells top and bottom for extra strength. Print two sets of handlebar brackets and one plate. The knob is printed large end down with no support. Pause the print at layer 24 and place a 6-32 nut in the hex shaped hole. Continue printing the remainder of the knob. Print two knobs. Cut threaded rod to size. (Tip: thread a nut on the rod before cutting. Touch up cut end with a file. Unthread the nut to straighten the treads.) Fix a nut to one end of the rod. (Glue or flatten the treads and back the nut onto it). Glue the long brackets in the slots on the platform. Attach the smaller brackets to the long brackets with the threaded rod and knobs. Place bracket over handlebars and tighten clamps until brackets are snug to handlebars. I used velcro to attached my GPS device to the platform.

Tired of all those empties rolling around in the back of your pickup?  Put them to work with this aluminum can construction set!  Also great for hours of fun in the break room.  
Each can clamp has 4 sets  of dovetail slots (2 at right angles).  The keys have double-sided mating dovetails  to interconnect them in a variety of configurations.  Short and long keys and the Tee adapters provide lots of flexibility.

All parts are designed for exactly 0.2mm layer thickness and exactly 0.4mm line width. Setting your slicer to these values will make them print much faster. No added supports are needed. (The can clamp has small supports built-in for the horizontal slots, and they break away easily.) Construction tips:

  • The short keys lock in with a friction fit if slid into slots on both sides.

  • The long keys have a slight bump on one side to provide a friction fit without being slid into a dovetail slot on both sides.

  • It is easiest if you first assemble the keys in the slots first and then slide in the cans.

  • For more stability, use one or two unopened cans in the base of your creation.

title: Mast mount for 48mm OD Aluminium pipe

description.text:
I needed a mobile mast mount for my Lenz2 Helical XL from thing 99132  
So I made some parts to make a somewhat mobile mast mount I can disassemble and is portable enough for car transport.  
I just thought I'd upload those parts here instead of sticking them under the turbine thing.

What I used to make this mount is 1 44x68mm 180cm of treated wooden pole for outside use. I made a slot in the wood to make a cross.  
I then drilled 4 7,5mm holes for the 4 feet, and 4 holes 7,5mm for the mast mount. I used a 20mm wood drill to counter sink the holes for about 10mm deep so that the hex head of the M8 bolts is countersunk into the beam.  
I ratcheted the 8 M8x100 bolts into the 8 holes so that the wire ends protrude from the top side. You can then fit the mount on top and fasten it with wing nuts. The mount has a few extra slide holes for easier transport without loosing everything.  
For reinforcement I made a collar to fit onto the mast to guide 4mm steel PVC coated wire. It used 2 M4x20 with 2 M4 Loc-nuts. Combined with the feet and end clamps this makes should be able to bear the wind load whilst being portable. For the end clamps you need 4 M3x16 bolts with loc-nuts a piece, for a total of 16. For the feet you need a M5x30 bolt with a wing nut.

description.text:
This is a piggy bank, made to look like a pirate chest. It's quite small (10cm by 6), can be used by our kids to hide treasure or their first coins.  
Loosely reworked from linked design, started from scratch but took quite a bit of inspiration. Designed entirely in inkscape, looking at the different slides might provide some additional idea on how it's been done.

Cut out of 3mm thick material (I used plywood, MDF should be fine) Red is for cutting
Blue is engraving (license)
Green is motif engraving
Pink is indication, don't print :-) Box is a trivial assembly: use glue, snap in place with a rubber hammer and use a press to hold tight Lid is a non trivial: link the arch (1) and the L-shaped piece (2) together (twice).

This is a laser scanning system that I designed to use with DAVID 3D Scanner software. I have yet to buy the software, but the free version really lets you try out everything before you buy...you can at least take some high resolution screenshots of your scans. You can save low resolution files and use meshlab to assemble them. More info at: http://www.david-laserscanner.com/ The first scanner I designed was complicated and used gears and a stepper motor, this one works much better. It's cheaper, requires no electricity to move and has less parts. It even tells you when it's done scanning! It uses a Taylor kitchen timer, this is a mechanical wound timer that you can purchase at Target, for about $3 PN: 5833-21 When combined with custom makerbot parts, two M3 screws/nuts and a red or green focus-able line laser you have a nice smoothly sweeping laser system.

Purchase Kitchen timer
Take off dial
Pinch and push out the 3 retaining pins
Print mount and press the mechanical housing into the printed mount.
Print the laser horn and while still warm put it on the center shaft so you get a good tight fit, make sure the screw holes are horizontal from each other, then let it fully cool.
Print the laser clip, mount to horn using M3 hex screws. Add a standard 12mm diameter line laser. (Dealextreme or Markerbot carries them) wire up your laser to a recommended power source. I usually have the laser pointing down and then I have to wind it clockwise to about the 20 minute position to make it sweep from the top of an object down. 
Print out the base, plus 3 supports & assemble or design a better one. Thread the base and the mount onto an M8 x 305mm rod or length of your choosing.
Go to www.david-laserscanner.com and get the software, free or buy. Print / make the background.
Fire up your webcam, follow the info on the the david website/in the software and start experimenting with 3d laser scanning.

I designed this so that I could try to print it on my 3D printer and I wanted to have a project that I could actually upload to Thingiverse because everything else I am working on is covered by Non-Disclosure Agreements. I hope to eventually have more time to work on my own 3D projects and upload them to CAD.  
I just updated this item to include some pictures of the actual 3d print and the file I used to print. I did this on an Ultimaker at Heatsync Labs. However, the prints did not turn out as well as I would like due to improper print settings. If I have time, I will refine them and print some better ones. I just printed two halves individually and will glue them together. Overall, this was a really fun and simple design.  
If you download it and print it, please send me a photo and let me know what kind of 3d printer you are using. I am hoping to find out which 3d printer can really print these out well and if you get a really good print, I will include its photo in the gallery and give you credit.  
Thanks for looking and comments are appreciated.

I had some time during my lunch break at work so I used NX 8.5 to quickly create this CAD model. It only took me five minutes to create Ninja Star 1, then I spent three minutes refining the design to create Ninja Star 2.0 and then another two minutes creating the drawing and screenshots.  
If you are going to print this, I would suggest doing a high resolution print using PLA, 0.1 mm layer heights, and a slow print speed.

Slip the ends and bottom on the power supply, and hold them in place with the keys. Simple!  
I'll probably update this a few times to make it prettier. Ideas being mulled over include clamp stands, bolt down options, wrap strap channels for mounting under a desk. What do you want to see?
